{
  "answer": "**The work is *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThe verse (58) states: \"*Let the fool speak thus, [...] the gall bladder [...]. Of the measure of the seven islands, the king becomes powerful. // 58*.\"[^2]\n\nThe immediately following prose gloss elaborates: \"Where is this great fool, who argues about its nature? It is said that the gall bladder is a thumb’s breadth in size. The gall bladder is as large as the seven islands. What are the seven islands? Such is the Lord Īśvara; He is of great power, all-pervading. Thus are the words of the fool. This is what is called the argument of a pandit.\"[^3]\n\nThis dismisses the 'great fool' (*maha-bala*, here rendered \"great fool\") who claims the gall bladder—described two paragraphs earlier as \"its measure [...] that of a thumb\"[^4]—is only a thumb's breadth, countering with the absurdly vast \"seven islands\" (a reference to the cosmic Jambudvīpa and its sub-continents in Indian cosmology).\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01-chapter-1/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01-chapter-1/translation/#p-a0c6ba).\n\n[^3]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01-chapter-1/translation/#p-135eac).\n\n[^4]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01-chapter-1/translation/#p-371134).",
